fields.descriptive_line: Living room accessories including a fireplace, paintings and a mirror, part of a dolls' house in the style of the 1940s made in England by Roma Hopkinson in the late 1980s to late 1990s.
fields.physical_description:
[cabinets (case furniture)] Living room setting with yellow floral wallpaper, brown parquet effect flooring, and three working light fittings. In the back left-hand corner of the room is a cupboard which goes under the stairs.
[desks] Wood and perspex cabinet containing painted ceramic plates, jugs, and statues.
[dressers (cupboards)] Wooden writing desk with two cupboards and nine drawers. Fixed to the desk are a number of accessories including a wireless, teacup and saucer, pencils, envelopes, books, and a lamp. The drawers contain miniature photographs, ration books, and identity cards.
[chairs] Wooden dresser with four shelves above two cupboards. The shelves contain a collection of novelty teapots and books.
[armchairs] Two brown leather effect chairs with light brown upholstered seat cushions. Fixed to the bottom are four brass effect feet.
[bookshelves] Wooden armchair upholstered in brown leather effect fabric.
[chess tables] Square wooden table with a clear perspex top. Fixed to the table is an ashtray, a box of matches, a box of cigarettes, a book, and a trinket box.
[folding chair] Wooden table with chess board and black and white plastic chess pieces in a metal container.
[end tables] Brown wooden chair with green leather effect seat. The seat unfolds to become a set of steps.
[sideboards (furniture)] Wooden end or side table with a single drawer containing a gold pair of scissors and a dress pattern. On top of the table is a small pink notebook.
[carpets] Wooden dining room table with two drop leaf ends. Fixed to the top of the table is a gold tray, flower arrangement, mug with the name Rosa written on it, a torch, a comb, and a pair of scissors. There are four chairs with the table which have brown leather effect upholstery.
[tiger rugs] Wooden sideboard with two cupboards and two drawers. The cupboard on the left side contains a red tablecloth and the cupboard on the right contains plastic glasses and a metal soda stream. The top drawer contains metal cutlery and the bottom drawer holds red and white candles. On top of the sideboard is a candlebra, two vases, a fishbowl, a metal tankard, and a painted tray with glassware.
[newspaper rack] Beige rug with a green, blue, and pink geometric pattern with cream fringing at each end.
[couches] Tiger skin effect rug with painted model clay head.
[animals] Wooden newspaper rack holding an assortment of magazines and newspapers from the 1940's.
[dolls' house equipment] Brown leather effect sofa with light brown upholstered seat cushions. Fixed to the bottom are five brass effect feet.
[doll's house accessories] Assortment of accessories and equipment including, three gas masks in boxes, a Singer sewing machine in a wooden box, a hoover and a carpet cleaner, a mantle clock, a banjo, a wooden chest, a typewriter, and a Box Brownie camera.
[room setting] Assortment of accessories and equipment including school certificates, identity cards, letters, ration books, photographs and photo albums, knitting, three hats and a tin helmet, books, torch, candles, pots and pans and fireplace tools.
[dining tables] Two model animals showing a sleeping cat and a dog.

fields.public_access_description: This house is a replica of a real house in Surrey where Roma Hopkinson lived with her family during the Second World War. Roma built this house in the 1980's, paying incredible attention to detail, reproducing ration books, identity cards, newspapers, and photo albums by reducing copies of the original versions. The photographs show her family as they appeared at that time. Each doll is also modelled on a family member with Roma appearing as one on of the children in a school dress. The house accurately reflects the wartime era, showing popular products, foodstuffs, games, and furnishings from the time.
fields.history_note: [dressers (cupboards)] The photographs, ration books, and identity cards are all scaled down versions of the originals owned by Roma Hopkinson.
